<div class="container">
    <div class="section">
        <h2>Celiac Disease Diagnosis</h2>
        <div class="image-container">
            <img src="/img/info/Screenshot 2025-03-11 150006-Photoroom.png" alt="Celiac Disease Illustration">
        </div>
        <p>
            Celiac disease is suspected if a person experiences digestive symptoms after consuming gluten. Therefore,
            it is important to conduct celiac disease tests before trying a gluten-free diet, as these tests reveal
            how gluten actually affects the body. Once a patient starts avoiding gluten, the intestines begin to
            recover.
        </p>

        <p>
            <span class="highlight">
                Healthcare providers use two methods to test for celiac disease, and it is
                preferable to use both together to confirm the diagnosis.
            </span>
        </p>
        <p>
            <span class="highlight"><b style="font-size: 20PX;">The First Method Is A Blood Test : </b></span>
            Healthcare providers test a blood
            sample for gluten antibodies that damage the intestines. The tTG IgA test and the total IgA test are
            used, as they are the most accurate and reliable.
        </p>
        <p>A positive tTG IgA result is above 4 U/mL, while a negative result is below 4 U/mL.</p>
        <p>
            A positive total IgA result is above 310 mg/dL for ages 17–60 years, and above 320 mg/dL for those aged
            61 and above.
        </p>
        <p>
            The levels of hemoglobin, iron, and nutrients such as vitamins and minerals in the blood are also
            analyzed to detect iron deficiency anemia or nutrient deficiencies caused by malnutrition.
        </p>
        <p>
            <span class="highlight"><b style="font-size: 20PX;">The Second Method Is A Biopsy : </b></span> If
            antibodies are detected in the
            blood, the doctor will take a biopsy to confirm the diagnosis. To obtain the biopsy, a
            gastroenterologist performs an endoscopy of the small intestine, takes a tissue sample, and examines it
            under a microscope to check for villous atrophy, which is the hallmark of celiac disease malabsorption.
        </p>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="container">

    <div class="section">

        <h2>Celiac Disease Treatment</h2>
        <div class="section flex-section" style="justify-content: space-between;">

            <div>
                <p>
                    The most important step in treating celiac disease is to stop consuming gluten, as it is not
                    possible
                    to
                    change the way the body reacts to gluten, but gluten can be prevented from triggering this
                    reaction.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Once gluten is eliminated from the diet, the small intestine will begin to heal and will soon be
                    able
                    to
                    absorb nutrients again.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="image">
